      <abstract>
        <p>We report two cases that demonstrate not only rare presentations of a rare disease, but accepted methods of hydatid management and the use of C.A.T. scanning in diagnosis and follow-up. They also confirm the value of operative cholangiography and perhaps introduce the use of a new anthelminthic agent, mebendazole, in association with surgery.</p>
      </abstract>
